<h1>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong> is used to describe a customary action.
<p></p>

<strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong> is used to describe a state which is the of the action expressed
by the verb. If the verb describes an action that can be repeated or continued,
<strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong> expresses the continuation of that action. Otherwise if the
verb expresses a momentary action, <strong>@Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}}</strong> expresses the idea
that the action happened and the resulting state continues. Verbs used in this construction
are intransitive ones.
<p></p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<h2> Notes </h2>

When the verb is one of motion, such as @HI{{kuru}} or @HI{{kaeru}}, 
the meaning is to have performed the motion and its results persist. 
For example, @HI{{itte iru}} means to have gone somewhere and still be there.
<p></p>

@HI{{sumu}} requires this sentence pattern if the sentence expresses a continuing state.
<p></p>

Verbs such as @HI{{iu}} and @HI{{omou}} require this sentence pattern if the subject is the
third person and the sentence expresses a present state.
<p></p>

